  "prompt": "How does magnesium oxide react with water?",
  "response": "Magnesium oxide (MgO) reacts with water to form magnesium hydroxide (Mg(OH)\u2082). The reaction proceeds as follows:\n\n\\[ MgO + H\u2082O \\rightarrow Mg(OH)\u2082 \\]\n\nThis reaction is not typically vigorous and requires water to be in liquid form. Magnesium hydroxide is only sparingly soluble in water, leading to the formation of a suspension known often as milk of magnesia, which is used medically to relieve indigestion and as a laxative.\n\nWhen magnesium oxide is added to water, the solid MgO dissolves slightly and forms Mg(OH)\u2082, which then precipitates out of the solution to form a solid, or it can stay as a suspended particle within the water.",
